04267nam a22006975i 9780691188089DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911880897 a10.1515/97806911880892doi  a(DE-B1597)501613  a(OCoLC)1076412342  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDT61b.M543 2005eb 7aHIS0020302bisacsh 7aSOC0020102bisacsh 7aSOC0030002bisacsh04a932.0142221 aMeskell, Lynn, eauthor.10aPrivate Life in New Kingdom Egypt /cLynn Meskell. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tConventions -- tChapter One.The Interpretative Framework -- tChapter Two. Locales and Communities -- tChapter Three. Social Selves -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Founding a House -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Love, Eroticism, and the Sexual Self -- tCHAPTER SIX. Embodied Knowledge -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Cycles of Death and Life -- tPostscript -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex  aMuch of the literature on ancient Egypt centers on pharaohs or on elite conceptions of the afterlife. This scintillating book examines how ordinary ancient Egyptians lived their lives. Drawing on the remarkably rich and detailed archaeological, iconographic, and textual evidence from some 450 years of the New Kingdom, as well as recent theoretical innovations from several fields, it reconstructs private and social life from birth to death. The result is a meaningful portrait composed of individual biographies, communities, and landscapes. Structured according to the cycles of life, the book relies on categories that the ancient Egyptians themselves used to make sense of their lives. Lynn Meskell gracefully sifts the evidence to reveal Egyptian domestic arrangements, social and family dynamics, sexuality, emotional experience, and attitudes toward the cadences of human life. She discusses how the Egyptians of the New Kingdom constituted and experienced self, kinship, life stages, reproduction, and social organization. And she examines their creation of communities and the material conditions in which they lived. Also included is neglected information on the formation of locality and the construction of gender and sexual identity and new evidence from the mortuary record, including important new data on the burial of children. Throughout, Meskell is careful to highlight differences among ancient Egyptians--the ways, for instance, that ethnicity, marital status, age, gender, and occupation patterned their experiences. Readers will come away from this book with new insights on how life may have been experienced and conceived of by ancient Egyptians in all their variety. This makes Private Life in New Kingdom Egypt unique in Egyptology and fascinating to read.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Egypt.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691188089zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691188089.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN